segments.text: Your thoughts about A&M now?
Yeah, I still think about the good old days.
Yeah.
All right.
Let's see, didn't we have some pictures that we were going to, as a physical plant on the campus?
Did anyone else come that you know of with him from A&M?
Mr. Craitman, Dr. Craitman.
Mr. Cradley was here.
Mr. Cradley was his secretary through the years, long years.
Finishing the new present home there, so we moved right into a brand new house, and it's very much, very much on a much smaller scale like the wonderful house at Marlin.
house 50 some years and that house has been completely redone then.
But it had been redone just the year 1925 when we moved up here.
So it was really a nice house and it was built by the first person we moved.
way back, of course.
And now they've made it a big place, so they built a big room on the back of it that seats 60 people, so you have university affairs.
But part of it is very much just those three.
three houses, and I just had the two.
So now you have that one.
Yes, I see right where it is.
Not very many people can say they've had three growing up childhood houses, and they've all been with Presley.
You're right.
And since I've been married, I've lived in three houses.
They're my own houses now.
So that's...
Now, when you got to the University of Texas, what did your major, what was your academic major?
History.
Good.
Good.
Well, you took anthropology, didn't you?
I understood that your father wanted anthropology.
What caused him to be interested in that subject?
I had no idea.
I had no idea until I got to the university, and that's what I was enrolled in.
My father was one that he just took over what I thought I should have, and that's what I took.
And did he look at your grades carefully each semester?
I don't know that he saw my grades, but they were, they got me through school, so I guess I don't know.
And you said you don't remember how much a semester cost, the tuition or anything?
No, I had nothing to do with paying for it, so I didn't.
Yes, when Reveille came to visit you.
Well, I had a little business to do with a broker, a young man, and he wanted me to come to his office, and I went to his office.
And I was sitting across the desk from him, and he was talking to me.
That's when he told me, Mike, do you understand me?
And I looked down at a table right next to my chair.
It was an ashtray.
And I took a double look.
It was at Texas A&M.
And so I immediately said, I said, you have a Texas A&M ashtray.
Did you go to Texas A&M?
Well, we from then on, we were just good friends, you know.
And we just talked more about it.
And so that summer, the freshman that was taking care of Reveille was here in Oklahoma City.
And I think they were having some kind of a layman meeting or something here.
And so they had him here with Reveille.
And so Ted asked him if he would come over.
He brought him over here and took his picture with the beautiful collie.
And then I got a framed copy of it.
And that's what she's going to see.
That was a real thrill for me.
Very good.
As I've heard it, somebody from A&M stole the owl.
The owl, yeah.
And a group of Rice students came up to get it.
Do you remember any more?
No.
I'd forgotten all about the incident, but I do remember now.
I had a picture of the owl.
I saw the picture.
